{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4e93526d-0971-43df-94c5-a99a75f4a4cb","content":"These are two distinct C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**Error 1 — `left && right` with `dynamic`**\n\nC# 15 now partially resolves user-defined logical operators (`&&`/`||`) at **compile time**, even when one operand is `dynamic`. Previously, the entire expression was deferred to runtime.\n\n`&&` is lowered to: `operator_true(left) ? left : left & right`. The compiler looks for `operator &(IFilter, ...)` on `IFilter` at compile time — but `IFilter` only defines `true`/`false`, not `&`. It fails before runtime ever gets involved.\n\n**Fixes** (pick one):\n- Add `operator &` to the interface:\n  ```csharp\n  static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;\n  ```\n- Cast `left` to `dynamic` to force full runtime binding:\n  ```csharp\n  var combined = (dynamic)left && right;\n  ```\n\n---\n\n**Error 2 — `ref readonly` lambda gives CS0518**\n\nCS0518 (\"predefined type is not defined or imported\") means the compiler is trying to synthesize a natural delegate type for your `ref readonly`-returning lambda, but the target framework is missing a required BCL type (likely a new attribute or delegate infrastructure type introduced in .NET 11).\n\nThis typically happens when the **compiler** is C# 15 but you're **targeting** an older runtime (e.g., `<TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>` or earlier).\n\n**Fixes** (pick one):\n- Target .NET 11: set `<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>` in your project file.\n- Declare an explicit delegate type to avoid synthesized type inference:\n  ```csharp\n  delegate ref readonly int RefReadonlyFunc();\n\n  public static void M()\n  {\n      RefReadonlyFunc fn = () => ref value;\n  }\n  ```\n- Use a local function instead of a lambda:\n  ```csharp\n  static ref readonly int Fn() => ref value;\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"23a1ea3a-1ac6-47f1-a91a-c1e924540291","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze each one:\n\n**Error 1: `left && right` where `left` is `IFilter` and `right` is `dynamic`**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a change related to how the `&&` operator interacts with `dynamic` operands when interface operators are involved.\n\nThe `&&` operator is a short-circuit operator that requires `operator true`, `operator false`, and `operator &` to be defined. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler historically deferred resolution to runtime. But with C# 15 introducing support for static abstract/virtual interface members more broadly, and changes to how operators on interfaces work, there could be a breaking change.\n\n\nThe compiler likely tightened its handling of the `&&` operator when one operand is `dynamic` and the other is an interface type with user-defined `operator true` and `operator false` members. This is a known breaking change in recent C# versions that affects how these logical operators resolve at compile time versus runtime. fail because `operator &` isn't defined on `IFilter`. The compiler now enforces this at compile time rather than deferring to runtime, which breaks code that previously relied on dynamic resolution to handle the mismatch. (IFilter, dynamic)` — this operator doesn't exist on the interface. Since one operand is `dynamic`, the old compiler would've deferred the whole thing to runtime, but now it seems the compiler is doing partial compile-time resolution and failing when it can't find the `&` operator, even though the actual runtime object might have it.\n\nFor the second error with `ref readonly int () => ref value`, the CS0518 error suggests the compiler can't find a predefined type it needs. With `ref readonly` return lambdas in newer C# versions, there might be a specific delegate type or attribute required that isn't being properly imported or defined. Actually, CS0518 \"Predefined type is not defined or imported\" suggests the runtime is missing a required type that the compiler expects. For `ref readonly` lambdas, this could mean the targeting pack doesn't include newer delegate types or BCL attributes needed to support this feature.\n\nLet me think about this differently though - these errors might stem from known C# 14/15 changes around dynamic types and compound operators. The stricter compile-time checking for `&&`/`||` with `dynamic` could be the culprit, since the compiler now validates whether `operator true`/`false` can be applied to the result of `operator &`/`|` at compile time rather than deferring to runtime. int` - the return type\n- `()` - no parameters  \n- `=> ref value` - the body returning a ref\n\nFor this to work as a natural delegate type, the compiler needs to create or find a delegate type. But there's no `Func<ref readonly int>` in the BCL. The compiler would need to synthesize one. If the compiler version supports this syntax but the underlying type system doesn't have the right pieces, CS0518 occurs.\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, this feature might be newly supported but requires specific runtime support types.\n\nSo the first error is about the compiler now enforcing stricter compile-time checks on the `&&` operator even with `dynamic` involved — `IFilter` needs an `operator &` defined, but it only has `operator &&`. Either declare an explicit delegate type with `ref readonly` return, ensure the correct .NET targeting pack is installed, or use a local function instead of a lambda. The core issue is that C# now resolves user-defined operators at compile time even with `dynamic` operands when the non-dynamic operand provides enough context — so for `left && right` where `left` is `IFilter` and `right` is `dynamic`, the compiler lowers it to check `operator true(left)` and then tries to find `operator &(IFilter, ???)`, which fails at compile time rather than deferring to runtime as it did before.\n\nFor the ref readonly lambda issue, the problem is that the compiler needs to synthesize a delegate type for a lambda with a `ref readonly` return, and CS0518 indicates a missing predefined type — likely something from `System.Runtime.CompilerServices` that's needed to support ref-returning lambdas in this context.\n\nThe fix would be either targeting .NET 11 or later where these types are available, or explicitly defining a delegate type instead of relying on inference.\n\nFor the first error, I'm realizing this is probably a C# 15 breaking change where compound assignment and logical operators with `dynamic` are now partially resolved at compile time. The `&&` operator now requires that `operator true`, `operator false`, and `operator &` all be applicable, so the compiler is checking `IFilter` for an `operator &` implementation that doesn't exist.\n\nFor the second error, it's about natural delegate types for ref-returning lambdas. The lambda returning `ref readonly int` needs a delegate type that can express that return type, and the compiler tries to synthesize one but can't find the necessary BCL infrastructure in the target framework—that's what CS0518 means.","outputTokens":3420,"requestId":"6802:2C5C9E:2C4656:39C0A1:69FFE37D"},"id":"56276beb-f473-425b-8026-abc8bc8d5723","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:47:50.551Z","parentId":"271c0fe4-636a-42fe-b5e5-f880cc36b4ca"}
